Events.RelatedDescription: Opened pull request "[monodroid] Use .aot extension for default aot profiler output" (#1254) at xamarin/xamarin-android
Events.RelatedBody:
When the profiler output filename is not set, we set our own, which is
written in the `.__override__` directory. It is now set to
`profile.aot` for the `aot` profiler and `.mlpd` for the `log`
profiler.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened pull request "[Tasks] Add aot to the list of valid profilers" (#1253) at xamarin/xamarin-android
Events.RelatedBody:
With this change it is possible to build an apk containing `aot`
profiler module (libmono-profiler-aot.so shared library) and profile
the app with it. It can enabled by setting `mono.debug.profile`
property to `aot` on the device or emulator.

Note that there is an issue with Java.Interop, where the app shutdown
is broken right now. We get unhandled exception and thus the shutdown
process doesn't finish, which means the profile output is not written
to the file. Hopefully I can fix that soon.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Camera doesn't work on Samsung Galaxy S7 with android 6.0.1" (#1252) at xamarin/xamarin-android
Events.RelatedBody:
### Steps to Reproduce

1. Install [this app](https://developer.xamarin.com/recipes/android/other_ux/camera_intent/take_a_picture_and_save_using_camera_app/) on Samsung Galaxy S7 with android 6.0.1
2. Press "OPEN CAMERA" button

Github: [link](https://github.com/xamarin/recipes/tree/master/android/other_ux/camera_intent/take_a_picture_and_save_using_camera_app)

### Expected Behavior
Camera opens in preview mode
### Actual Behavior
Camera is failure to open
### Additional info
Camera works properly on Samsung Galaxy S7 with android 7.0
### Version Information
- Samsung Galaxy S7 with android 6.0.1

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "Can't override GetAutofillOptions in ArrayAdapter class." (#1250) at xamarin/xamarin-android
Events.RelatedBody:
### Steps to Reproduce

1. Create some class, e.g. with name TestClass
2. Extend it from Android.Widget.ArrayAdapter
3. override GetAutofillOptions method

### Expected Behavior
Method can be overridden.

### Actual Behavior
Error: There is no suitable method for override

### Version Information
[VS_info.txt](https://github.com/xamarin/xamarin-android/files/1678126/VS_info.txt)

### Comment
I was converting this line of code:
https://github.com/googlesamples/android-AutofillFramework/blob/16625cf003034585cefc882a165e2f1fae58634e/Application/src/main/java/com/example/android/autofill/app/commoncases/CreditCardSpinnersActivity.java#L82

In Java Adapter interface has definition of this mehod
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5435980/35572664-c8021bd4-05dd-11e8-8a87-c47564b7b765.png)

In .Net we had't such method definition
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5435980/35572710-de80160e-05dd-11e8-994a-d04ad33edde1.png)

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Allow Windows build/installer to include proprietary assemblies" (#1251) at xamarin/xamarin-android
Events.RelatedBody:
When building on Windows, we should allow both the `.msi` and `setup-windows.exe` to *optionally* use and install existing proprietary assemblies already present on the build machine.

When such proprietary assemblies are used, a warning message should be written at the end of packaging/installation.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Race condition between the main thread and a thread used by CADisplayLinkTicker" (#1755) at xamarin/Xamarin.Forms
Events.RelatedBody:
Bug report best practices: https://github.com/xamarin/Xamarin.Forms/wiki/Submitting-Issues

### Description

Race condition between the main thread and a thread used by CADisplayLinkTicker
CADisplayLinkTicker invokes Quartz.CATransaction.commi()t which is deciding to do an auto layout while not on the main thread, in the main thread we are adding/removing ContentViews (Note class in our code) to an AbsoluteLayout

This makes the iOS version of our app to crash.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "[Enhancement] Rounded Corners" (#1754) at xamarin/Xamarin.Forms
Events.RelatedBody:
## Rationale

Rounded corners are a common visual requirement which Forms does not support without custom renderers. Forms should provide a common interface for defining rounded corners on Views.

## Implemenation

We need to add an interface for defining what's required for a View to implement corner rounding (and provide CSS support):

```csharp
interface IRoundedCorners
{
	CornerRadius CornerRadius { get; }
	void CornerRadiusChanged(CornerRadius oldValue, CornerRadius newValue);
}
```

The CornerRadius BindableProperty can be implemented in one place:

```
static class RoundedCornerElement
{
	public static readonly BindableProperty CornerRadiusProperty = BindableProperty.Create(nameof(CornerRadius), typeof(CornerRadius), typeof(IRoundedCorners));
}
```

Renderer implementations should be careful to take [Borders](https://github.com/xamarin/Xamarin.Forms/issues/1695) into consideration.

The following Views are candidates for rounded corners:
BoxView (in progress: https://github.com/xamarin/Xamarin.Forms/issues/1709)
ImageView
StackLayout
Grid
AbsoluteLayout
ScrollView
(probably others)

## Difficulty: Easy
Providing the interface is simple; individual implementations may vary in difficulty.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened pull request "Ensure Android PanGestureRecognizer sends the Completed status (#1495)" (#1753) at xamarin/Xamarin.Forms
Events.RelatedBody:
### Description of Change ###

The ScaleGestureDetector in Android doesn't always fire an end gesture event. It seems we rely upon this to fire the EndScrolling method. 

If we also listen for the touch up event, we can call EndScrolling event if the ScaleGestureDetector fails to fire.

I'm not opposed to moving the TapAndPanGestureDetector to it's own file, if you prefer.

### Bugs Fixed ###

[Issue #1495](https://github.com/xamarin/Xamarin.Forms/issues/1495)

### API Changes ###

None

### Behavioral Changes ###

None

### PR Checklist ###

- [ ] Has tests (if omitted, state reason in description)
- [ ] Rebased on top of master at time of PR
- [ ] Changes adhere to coding standard
- [ ] Consolidate commits as makes sense

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "Unable to pin UISplitView to superView (ignore safe areas)" (#3164) at xamarin/xamarin-macios
Events.RelatedBody:
### Steps to Reproduce

1. Enable "Use safe areas" in storyboard
2. Add UISplitView to the storyboard
3. Add UITableView into splitView
4. Try to pin UITableView left and right to the superView (not to the safeAreas to follow iPhone X design pattern). 

### Expected Behavior
Will be able to choose the SuperView or SafeArea in Xamarin interface builder while adding new constraints (same like in Xcode).

### Actual Behavior
Unable to choose superView. It's always pinned to the safeArea so there is a white space on the left and right side when the device (iPhone X) is in landscape mode

### Workaround
There was a workaround to open the storyboard in XCode, but according to the Xamarin docs, this is not recommended anymore. It also breaks my storyboard so I am not able to compile the project after opening it in XCode (it break's the storyboard XML so it's not readable for the compiler anymore)

### Environment
iOS 11.2, iPhone X - landscape mode
Visual Studio For Mac - 7.3.2 - build 12
iOS Designer Extension - 7.3
iOS development Extension - 7.3.2

### Build Logs
No problem with the build - this issue is interface designer related - unable to select the parent while pinning (or change it in constraint preferences like in XCode)

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened pull request "[msbuild] Use the proper MM vs MT error code prefix" (#3360) at xamarin/xamarin-macios
Events.RelatedBody:
Up until now, when building Xamarin.Mac projects, any existing errors in MSBuild that have already been error-codeified would always log the error using the MT prefix instead of MM.

This fixes that and also makes logging more consistent with the base logging methods, but allowing for a more simplified integer error code value rather than a string.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Add a StrongDictionary to SecKey.GenerateKeyPair" (#3359) at xamarin/xamarin-macios
Events.RelatedBody:
While [PR 3350](https://github.com/xamarin/xamarin-macios/pull/3350): "[Security] Refactoring Sec-keys" is a good step toward making `SecKey.GenerateKeyPair` more usable (by making some internal keys public), I believe we should consider adding an API with a strong dictionary.

The discussion in https://developer.apple.com/documentation/security/1395339-seckeygeneratepair?language=objc explains exactly which keys and also which keys of the `kSecPublicKeyAttrs` and `kSecPrivateKeyAttrs`'s respective dictionaries must be used.

We should map those to a StrongDictionary which provides intelliSense and help use the right keys.

Security framework method to improve: https://github.com/xamarin/xamarin-macios/blob/master/src/Security/Certificate.cs#L531-L545
